76
00:04:52,067 --> 00:04:54,399
Mm, beat me to
the paper again,

77
00:04:54,400 --> 00:04:55,600
huh, you little newshound?

78
00:04:55,634 --> 00:04:57,034
It's the only
day of the week

79
00:04:57,067 --> 00:04:59,367
when they let the
comics be in color.

80
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:01,634
You don't mind if I read
the Op-Ed section before you,

81
00:05:01,667 --> 00:05:03,500
do you?

82
00:05:03,534 --> 00:05:05,001
Where's Mommy?

83
00:05:05,034 --> 00:05:07,467
She had to
go into work.

84
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:09,101
On a Sunday?

85
00:05:09,134 --> 00:05:13,600
Apparently, crime does not
work a five-day week.

86
00:05:13,634 --> 00:05:15,700
Will she be
coming back soon?

87
00:05:15,734 --> 00:05:16,934
Uh, I don't know.

88
00:05:16,967 --> 00:05:18,268
But she said

89
00:05:18,333 --> 00:05:21,333
she was gonna help me
with my diorama this afternoon.

90
00:05:21,367 --> 00:05:23,268
Relax, Bridge, relax.

91
00:05:23,300 --> 00:05:26,867
No diorama drama, okay?

92
00:05:26,901 --> 00:05:29,168
I'm happy to fill in for Mommy.

93
00:05:29,201 --> 00:05:30,201
There was an ATM

94
00:05:30,234 --> 00:05:31,367
right around
the corner.

95
00:05:31,400 --> 00:05:32,801
He had a receipt
in his pocket.

96
00:05:32,834 --> 00:05:35,967
Apparently, he'd just
withdrawn $500.

97
00:05:36,001 --> 00:05:37,700
Whoever it was took
the cash, his watch,

98
00:05:37,734 --> 00:05:40,101
left everything else.

99
00:05:40,134 --> 00:05:42,467
Driver's license says
his name is Morgan Turley.

100
00:05:42,500 --> 00:05:45,268
Has his family
been notified?

101
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:48,367
So far, we haven't been able
to locate any.

102
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:49,834
What about his friends?

103
00:05:49,867 --> 00:05:51,500
Most of the numbers
in his cell phone

104
00:05:51,534 --> 00:05:52,767
were for take-out places.

105
00:05:52,801 --> 00:05:55,400
We're still running
everything down.

106
00:05:55,433 --> 00:05:56,967
Apparently,
he was self-employed.

107
00:05:57,001 --> 00:05:58,367
We found a businescard.

108
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:00,234
Worked out of his apartment.

109
00:06:00,268 --> 00:06:02,333
I fear this is not
someone a whole lot

110
00:06:02,367 --> 00:06:04,700
of people are
going to miss.

111
00:06:21,867 --> 00:06:23,434
You okay?

112
00:06:27,434 --> 00:06:29,767
<i>That so doesn't look
like George Washington.</i>

113
00:06:29,801 --> 00:06:31,434
Does, too.

114
00:06:31,467 --> 00:06:33,934
Looks more like an old lady
in a funny hat to me.

115
00:06:33,968 --> 00:06:35,767
Tell her it's George
Washington, Dad.

116
00:06:35,801 --> 00:06:38,300
It is absolutely
George Washington.

117
00:06:38,334 --> 00:06:40,033
In fact,
I will stake my reputation

118
00:06:40,067 --> 00:06:42,067
as a diorama-maker
on it.

119
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:44,934
However, you bring up an
interesting point, Ariel,

120
00:06:44,968 --> 00:06:46,133
one that many
young scholars

121
00:06:46,167 --> 00:06:48,567
like yourself
have pointed out.

122
00:06:48,601 --> 00:06:50,868
Apparently, any number
of our founding fathers,

123
00:06:50,901 --> 00:06:52,634
when viewed in
historical paintings,

124
00:06:52,667 --> 00:06:55,734
bear an uncanny resemblance
to old ladies in funny hats.

125
00:06:55,767 --> 00:06:58,667
Yeah, that's what
men wore back then.

126
00:06:58,701 --> 00:06:59,701
White wigs and
weird hats.

127
00:06:59,734 --> 00:07:01,100
It's not their fault

128
00:07:01,133 --> 00:07:02,868
that's what grandmas
dress likethesedays.

129
00:07:02,901 --> 00:07:05,267
Bridge, I'm sorry,

130
00:07:05,300 --> 00:07:08,033
but grandmas don't even dress
likethatanymore.

131
00:07:09,767 --> 00:07:11,300
I'm Morgan,
by the way.

132
00:07:11,334 --> 00:07:13,100
Morgan Turley.

133
00:07:16,734 --> 00:07:19,801
No.

134
00:07:19,834 --> 00:07:22,000
Uh-uh. Uh-uh.

135
00:07:22,033 --> 00:07:23,334
This is
really nuts.

136
00:07:23,367 --> 00:07:24,767
No, i-it's not nuts.

137
00:07:24,801 --> 00:07:28,467
It's, it's just the way
that it works.

138
00:07:28,501 --> 00:07:30,033
It's me.

139
00:07:30,067 --> 00:07:32,601
I've just passed on,
just like you have.

140
00:07:32,634 --> 00:07:36,934
I-I, I know it sounds crazy,
but once you accept it,

141
00:07:36,968 --> 00:07:41,033
once you embrace it,
it actually feels pretty good.

142
00:07:43,934 --> 00:07:45,300
Come on.

143
00:07:45,334 --> 00:07:47,868
Let me show you something.

144
00:07:54,434 --> 00:07:57,200
*

145
00:08:02,567 --> 00:08:04,400
I know it's hard to look at.

146
00:08:04,434 --> 00:08:05,667
I know it's hard to accept,

147
00:08:05,701 --> 00:08:08,067
but... you can't spend
the rest of forever

148
00:08:08,100 --> 00:08:10,400
running through the streets
in your underwear.

149
00:08:30,501 --> 00:08:33,000
Doesn't really look
like a millionaire, does she?

150
00:08:33,033 --> 00:08:34,501
Is she?

151
00:08:34,534 --> 00:08:35,534
Well, she
will be soon.

152
00:08:35,567 --> 00:08:37,067
That's Cadence Bixby.

153
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:38,534
She's Morgan Turley's
sole heir.

154
00:08:39,567 --> 00:08:41,434
Washea millionaire?
No,

155
00:08:41,467 --> 00:08:44,033
but he had a life insurance
policy worth that much,

156
00:08:44,067 --> 00:08:45,367
and since she's
the only beneficiary,

157
00:08:45,400 --> 00:08:47,868
she wants to offer a reward
for any information

158
00:08:47,901 --> 00:08:49,367
leading to the capture
of his killer.

159
00:08:49,400 --> 00:08:50,367
Wow.

160
00:08:50,400 --> 00:08:51,501
Is she family?

161
00:08:51,534 --> 00:08:53,534
Actually,
she barely knew him.

162
00:08:53,567 --> 00:08:54,534
I don't get it.

163
00:08:54,567 --> 00:08:56,334
Well, apparently,
our boy Morgan

164
00:08:56,367 --> 00:08:57,334
really liked cats.

165
00:08:57,367 --> 00:08:58,567
Ms. Bixby

166
00:08:58,601 --> 00:09:01,033
over there was just
explaining in great detail

167
00:09:01,067 --> 00:09:03,167
how she rescues strays
in her free time.

168
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:05,234
Brings dozens of the little
critters in off the streets,

169
00:09:05,267 --> 00:09:07,868
cleans them up,
tries to find them homes.

170
00:09:07,901 --> 00:09:09,634
Long story short,
Morgan adopted six of them

171
00:09:09,667 --> 00:09:12,200
from her
over the past two years.

172
00:09:12,234 --> 00:09:14,934
Anyway, her coffee's
getting cold.

173
00:09:14,968 --> 00:09:16,634
Well, wait a second.

174
00:09:16,667 --> 00:09:19,434
I wanted to ask you: has
that second body turned up yet?

175
00:09:19,467 --> 00:09:21,133
Mr. Underwear?

176
00:09:21,167 --> 00:09:22,567
No, but, uh, if
I hear anything,

177
00:09:22,601 --> 00:09:24,100
you'll be the
first to know.

178
00:09:24,133 --> 00:09:28,200
FYI, uh, I've been asked by
Ms. Bixby to spread the word

179
00:09:28,234 --> 00:09:29,801
there's going to be
a memorial service

180
00:09:29,834 --> 00:09:32,634
for Mr. Turley at Our Lady
of Sorrows tonight at 7:00.

181
00:09:32,667 --> 00:09:35,300
I hear all the coolest cats and
kittens are going to be there,

182
00:09:35,334 --> 00:09:38,234
so if you're hoping to get a
good seat, I'd sashay in early.

183
00:09:38,267 --> 00:09:39,400
Mm...

184
00:09:39,434 --> 00:09:40,467
Okay, explain it

185
00:09:40,501 --> 00:09:42,000
to me one more time
why you're going

186
00:09:42,033 --> 00:09:44,300
to a memorial service for a man
that you didn't even know.

187
00:09:44,334 --> 00:09:46,400
Because he has no one.

188
00:09:46,434 --> 00:09:49,234
He's leaving all his money
to a perfect stranger,

189
00:09:49,267 --> 00:09:50,801
for goodness' sake.

190
00:09:50,834 --> 00:09:53,934
And that's your
problem because...?

191
00:09:53,968 --> 00:09:56,334
Well, he's not leaving
the money to you, is he?

192
00:09:56,367 --> 00:09:59,033
Look, I've been dreaming
about this man for, what,

193
00:09:59,067 --> 00:10:00,234
two days now?

194
00:10:00,267 --> 00:10:02,300
Presumably,
there's a reason.

195
00:10:02,334 --> 00:10:04,634
Maybe it's to help figure out
who did this to him.

196
00:10:04,667 --> 00:10:06,701
Or maybe it's to be there
when the few people

197
00:10:06,734 --> 00:10:08,133
that he encountered
in his life

198
00:10:08,167 --> 00:10:10,200
gather together
to say good-bye.

199
00:10:10,234 --> 00:10:11,567
I'm not smart enough
to know.

200
00:10:11,601 --> 00:10:13,968
But I have been doing this
long enough to know

201
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:15,234
that something
about this man--

202
00:10:15,267 --> 00:10:18,167
his or his death,
maybe-- matters.

203
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:20,601
Yeah, it's just that yesterday
you weren't home.

204
00:10:20,634 --> 00:10:21,634
Tonight, you're going out.

205
00:10:21,667 --> 00:10:23,100
Which reminds me.

206
00:10:23,133 --> 00:10:25,000
I saw Bridgette's diorama
in the kitchen.

207
00:10:25,033 --> 00:10:26,501
Who's the old lady
in the boat?

208
00:10:26,534 --> 00:10:28,167
You don't get to do that.

209
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:30,300
What? Did I say something wrong?

210
00:10:30,334 --> 00:10:32,400
If you're not here,
you don't get to critique.

211
00:10:32,434 --> 00:10:33,501
(laughs)
Har-dee-har-har.

212
00:10:33,534 --> 00:10:34,934
It wasn't an old
lady in the boat?

213
00:10:34,968 --> 00:10:35,968
That's George Washington,

214
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:37,033
the father of our country,

215
00:10:37,067 --> 00:10:38,701
and if you don't like
the way he looks,

216
00:10:38,734 --> 00:10:40,033
I'm sorry.
then you should stay home

217
00:10:40,067 --> 00:10:41,701
the next time your daughter
has a project.

218
00:10:41,734 --> 00:10:42,968
Okay, I'm sorry,
I didn't know.

219
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:44,534
They all looked like that
back then.

220
00:10:44,567 --> 00:10:46,801
Joe, I'm sorry.

221
00:10:46,834 --> 00:10:47,968
I'd like to thank

222
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,934
Pastor Grimes again
for his lovely eulogy.

223
00:10:51,968 --> 00:10:54,767
And for allowing me to get up
here and say a few words

224
00:10:54,801 --> 00:10:56,667
about my good friend, Morgan.

225
00:10:56,701 --> 00:10:59,267
Morgan was a quiet man,

226
00:10:59,300 --> 00:11:01,534
a shy man.

227
00:11:01,567 --> 00:11:06,567
Deep down, I guess...
a lonely man.

228
00:11:07,601 --> 00:11:11,067
He kept mostly
to himself.

229
00:11:11,100 --> 00:11:14,167
It took time to get
to know Morgan.

230
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:16,801
It took effort.

231
00:11:16,834 --> 00:11:22,801
We grew up together,
so I had an advantage.

232
00:11:22,834 --> 00:11:24,901
We knew each
other's secrets.

233
00:11:24,934 --> 00:11:28,767
And one of Morgan's
biggest secrets

234
00:11:28,801 --> 00:11:31,501
was that he was happiest
by himself.

235
00:11:31,534 --> 00:11:35,767
Happiest in his apartment.

236
00:11:35,801 --> 00:11:38,801
Once or twice a month, I
could usually drag him out

237
00:11:38,834 --> 00:11:41,334
to a movie or
a ball game.

238
00:11:41,367 --> 00:11:44,067
But that was it
for him.

239
00:11:44,100 --> 00:11:46,968
Pleasure in
small doses.

240
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:50,300
That was all
he could handle.

241
00:11:50,334 --> 00:11:52,300
I'm gonna miss him.

242
00:11:53,834 --> 00:11:57,901
The talks after we would
leave the theater.

243
00:11:59,334 --> 00:12:01,534
Or just sitting
in his apartment,

244
00:12:01,567 --> 00:12:04,701
staring out the window.

245
00:12:04,734 --> 00:12:07,100
His favorite way to deal
with the world.

246
00:12:08,859 --> 00:12:10,432
Good-bye Morgan.

247
00:12:10,532 --> 00:12:12,299
You were a good man

248
00:12:12,333 --> 00:12:14,799
and a great friend.

249
00:12:14,832 --> 00:12:17,164
Mr. Turley?

250
00:12:19,789 --> 00:12:22,589
I'm glad you were
able to see this.

251
00:12:22,623 --> 00:12:24,290
I'm glad that you
were able to see

252
00:12:24,323 --> 00:12:25,890
that people really do care.

253
00:12:30,689 --> 00:12:33,489
You can see me?

254
00:12:33,522 --> 00:12:34,990
You know that I'm here?

255
00:12:36,990 --> 00:12:38,422
This is weird.

256
00:12:38,456 --> 00:12:39,823
You don't look dead.

257
00:12:39,856 --> 00:12:41,090
I'm not.

258
00:12:41,123 --> 00:12:42,856
It's a long story.

