of your life?

521
00:25:02,334 --> 00:25:04,467
And that would change
my life how, exactly?

522
00:25:04,500 --> 00:25:06,367
I'm begging you,
put a stop to this.

523
00:25:06,400 --> 00:25:07,866
No good can come of this.

524
00:25:07,900 --> 00:25:09,801
Tell me what really
happened in that alley.

525
00:25:09,866 --> 00:25:10,933
Who shot you?

526
00:25:10,966 --> 00:25:12,434
Why? Why do you care?

527
00:25:12,467 --> 00:25:13,667
You ever heard of the expression

528
00:25:13,701 --> 00:25:16,167
"die in peace"?

529
00:25:16,200 --> 00:25:18,100
Ms. Bixby, it's

530
00:25:18,133 --> 00:25:20,167
my understanding that when you
came to see Detective Scanlon

531
00:25:20,200 --> 00:25:23,334
the other day, you told him you
hardly knew Morgan Turley.

532
00:25:23,367 --> 00:25:26,033
That's true.
I run a small,

533
00:25:26,067 --> 00:25:27,500
non-profit
shelter for cats.

534
00:25:27,534 --> 00:25:31,033
I take in strays,
try to find them homes.

535
00:25:31,067 --> 00:25:33,267
One day, Mr. Turley just
walked through the door.

536
00:25:33,300 --> 00:25:36,067
Said he loved cats, was
wondering if he could adopt one.

537
00:25:36,100 --> 00:25:37,400
Is that a crime?

538
00:25:37,434 --> 00:25:39,334
And that's it?

539
00:25:39,367 --> 00:25:42,500
That's the extent
of your relationship?

540
00:25:42,534 --> 00:25:44,966
Well, it actually
happened a number of times.

541
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:47,300
I believe he ultimately
ended up adopting

542
00:25:47,334 --> 00:25:48,534
about a half dozen strays.

543
00:25:48,567 --> 00:25:51,300
Sounds like a nice man.

544
00:25:51,334 --> 00:25:52,767
He seemed so.

545
00:25:52,801 --> 00:25:54,233
Ms. Bixby, didn't
you find it odd

546
00:25:54,267 --> 00:25:55,866
that someone you barely knew

547
00:25:55,900 --> 00:25:57,467
would leave you
so much money?

548
00:25:57,500 --> 00:25:58,866
Of course.

549
00:25:58,900 --> 00:26:00,467
It's been overwhelming.

550
00:26:00,500 --> 00:26:03,067
Morgan Turley has
changed my life.

551
00:26:03,100 --> 00:26:05,200
I can only guess
that the cats

552
00:26:05,233 --> 00:26:07,300
I placed with him
gave him great joy,

553
00:26:07,334 --> 00:26:09,634
that he was looking
for a way to say thank you,

554
00:26:09,667 --> 00:26:13,300
to support the work that made
those adoptions possible,

555
00:26:13,334 --> 00:26:17,100
But why leave that money
to you, specifically?

556
00:26:17,133 --> 00:26:19,334
He didn't leave
it to your shelter.

557
00:26:19,367 --> 00:26:21,600
He didn't leave it
to any of the bigger,

558
00:26:21,634 --> 00:26:24,067
better known organizations
that do similar work.

559
00:26:24,100 --> 00:26:25,567
What do you mean "why"?

560
00:26:25,600 --> 00:26:27,367
Because I trust her.

561
00:26:27,400 --> 00:26:28,933
Because it was my money.

562
00:26:28,966 --> 00:26:31,300
I could do whatever the hell
I wanted to with it.

563
00:26:31,334 --> 00:26:33,833
Oh, my goodness.

564
00:26:33,866 --> 00:26:35,701
You think that I
might have something

565
00:26:35,734 --> 00:26:37,100
to do with his murder,

566
00:26:37,133 --> 00:26:39,133
don't you?
No. No one's saying that.

567
00:26:39,167 --> 00:26:40,801
We're exploring all
sorts of possibilities,

568
00:26:40,833 --> 00:26:42,100
but it'd be helpful
if you could tell us

569
00:26:42,133 --> 00:26:44,000
where you were this
past Saturday night.

570
00:26:44,033 --> 00:26:47,500
Is there anyone
who can vouch for
your whereabouts?

571
00:26:47,534 --> 00:26:50,133
No.

572
00:26:50,167 --> 00:26:51,966
I was home.

573
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:53,434
But I was by myself.

574
00:26:56,500 --> 00:26:57,734
Am I in trouble?

575
00:26:57,767 --> 00:26:59,067
Do I need a lawyer?

576
00:27:06,267 --> 00:27:08,534
I'm begging you--
look at her.

577
00:27:08,567 --> 00:27:10,167
Is that the face
of a killer?

578
00:27:10,200 --> 00:27:11,866
Is that the face of
a person who could

579
00:27:11,900 --> 00:27:13,767
pull the trigger on
another human being?

580
00:27:13,801 --> 00:27:16,300
She rescues pussycats
for God's sake!

581
00:27:16,334 --> 00:27:18,000
So you never
had any contact

582
00:27:18,033 --> 00:27:20,367
with Mr. Turley
outside of the shelter?

583
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:22,133
You didn't know him
in any context

584
00:27:22,167 --> 00:27:25,933
except as a man who was
interested in adopting cats?

585
00:27:25,966 --> 00:27:27,900
When they first called
to tell me he had passed away

586
00:27:27,933 --> 00:27:30,167
and left me his
insurance money,

587
00:27:30,200 --> 00:27:31,767
I couldn't even
remember who he was.

588
00:27:31,801 --> 00:27:33,866
What did I tell you?
Come on, Mrs. Dubois.

589
00:27:33,900 --> 00:27:34,966
You can put a
stop to this.

590
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:37,767
You can do it.

591
00:27:37,801 --> 00:27:40,133
Did you know you
were neighbors?
Oh, no.

592
00:27:40,167 --> 00:27:42,801
No, no, no.
Don't tell her that!
Really?

593
00:27:42,833 --> 00:27:45,367
I believe he lived directly
across the street from you.

594
00:27:45,400 --> 00:27:47,966
And who knows, maybe you can
see his apartment from yours?

595
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:50,833
Wouldn't that be
an amazing coincidence.

596
00:27:50,866 --> 00:27:53,334
And maybe he could see

597
00:27:53,367 --> 00:27:56,167
your apartment from his.

598
00:27:56,200 --> 00:27:59,567
Oh.

599
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:01,334
Okay. I give.

600
00:28:01,367 --> 00:28:03,033
I'll tell you anything
you want to know.

601
00:28:03,067 --> 00:28:04,567
Just don't tell
her anything else.

602
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:06,534
Don't ask her
anything else.

603
00:28:06,567 --> 00:28:08,634
Isn't there any way
we can check on that?

604
00:28:08,667 --> 00:28:09,966
Excuse yourself.

605
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:11,801
Right now. Let's go
out into the hallway,

606
00:28:11,833 --> 00:28:13,933
and I'll tell
you everything.
Perhaps.

607
00:28:13,966 --> 00:28:15,267
Can you excuse me a second?

608
00:28:15,300 --> 00:28:16,701
I need to step outside.

609
00:28:16,734 --> 00:28:18,833
I need to check on something.
I'll be right back.

610
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:23,801
I did it.
You did what?

611
00:28:23,833 --> 00:28:24,900
I killed myself.

612
00:28:24,933 --> 00:28:26,067
You did not.

613
00:28:26,100 --> 00:28:27,233
Did, too.

614
00:28:27,267 --> 00:28:28,334
Cross my heart and hope to die.

615
00:28:28,367 --> 00:28:29,600
Ask anybody who knows me.

616
00:28:29,634 --> 00:28:31,334
I've always talked
about killing myself.

617
00:28:31,367 --> 00:28:33,767
That's not funny,
and that's not true.

618
00:28:33,801 --> 00:28:35,233
There's nothing
about your injuries

619
00:28:35,267 --> 00:28:36,767
that are consistent
with suicide.

620
00:28:36,801 --> 00:28:38,434
Besides, everyone knows,

621
00:28:38,467 --> 00:28:40,767
life insurance doesn't
pay off on suicides.

622
00:28:40,801 --> 00:28:42,833
If you prove it was a suicide.

623
00:28:42,866 --> 00:28:44,434
Which we can't because it isn't.

624
00:28:44,467 --> 00:28:46,000
Well, then...

625
00:28:46,033 --> 00:28:47,534
I guess we're at a standoff.

626
00:28:47,567 --> 00:28:50,267
Really? I was just
thinking of taking Cadence

627
00:28:50,300 --> 00:28:51,767
for a little tour of your place.

628
00:28:51,801 --> 00:28:53,701
Checking out the cats,
showing her

629
00:28:53,734 --> 00:28:55,434
your view from your
living room window.

630
00:28:55,467 --> 00:28:56,767
No!

631
00:28:56,801 --> 00:28:59,033
Yes!
Oh, no.

632
00:28:59,067 --> 00:29:02,100
Don't tell me you're
dragging him into this, too?

633
00:29:02,133 --> 00:29:04,000
I'm sorry to
bother you.

634
00:29:04,033 --> 00:29:05,300
Do you work here?

635
00:29:05,334 --> 00:29:06,933
Yes, I do.

636
00:29:06,966 --> 00:29:09,133
I'm looking for
my fianc, Cadence?

637
00:29:09,167 --> 00:29:10,400
Cadence Bixby?

638
00:29:10,434 --> 00:29:12,567
Your fianc?
Your fianc?

639
00:29:12,600 --> 00:29:13,966
Do you know where
she might be?

640
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:16,267
She's right in there.

641
00:29:17,300 --> 00:29:19,300
Thanks.

642
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:24,567
You never told me that
Cadence and Nick were...

643
00:29:28,878 --> 00:29:30,978
That's it, I'm done.

644
00:29:31,012 --> 00:29:32,878
The guy doesn't care
about catching his killer,

645
00:29:32,912 --> 00:29:34,945
why should I?

646
00:29:36,379 --> 00:29:38,745
It's just so strange.

647
00:29:38,778 --> 00:29:41,112
You'd think the way he
always kept an eye on her,

648
00:29:41,145 --> 00:29:43,878
he'd have a clue that she was
involved with his best friend.

649
00:29:43,912 --> 00:29:46,412
Do I feel sorry
for the guy? Absolutely.

650
00:29:46,446 --> 00:29:50,379
Am I gonna lose any more
sleep over him? No.

651
00:29:50,412 --> 00:29:52,212
Me, either.

652
00:29:56,179 --> 00:29:58,611
Okay.

653
00:29:58,645 --> 00:30:01,245
I'm ready.

654
00:30:01,279 --> 00:30:04,312
Pull the trigger.

655
00:30:04,345 --> 00:30:06,312
You sure about this?

656
00:30:14,978 --> 00:30:18,711
Don't back out on me, Nick.

657
00:30:18,745 --> 00:30:20,345
Please.

658
00:30:20,379 --> 00:30:22,312
I'm begging you.

659
00:30:25,245 --> 00:30:26,611
With friends

660
00:30:26,645 --> 00:30:28,112
like that, huh?

661
00:30:30,179 --> 00:30:32,745
I don't understand.

662
00:30:32,778 --> 00:30:34,845
Morgan wanted to die?

663
00:30:34,878 --> 00:30:36,745
That was before he knew
his best pal

664
00:30:36,778 --> 00:30:39,279
was shacking up
with the girl he loved.

665
00:30:39,312 --> 00:30:41,645
Now, I think he's having
second thoughts.

666
00:30:43,397 --> 00:30:46,045
Did you send me
that dream, Mr. DiScala?

667
00:30:46,079 --> 00:30:48,912
I know you've been
trying to help him.

668
00:30:48,945 --> 00:30:51,912
Considering the hit
the poor guy took today,

669
00:30:51,945 --> 00:30:54,212
I thought you ought
to know the truth.

670
00:31:15,279 --> 00:31:17,578
You okay?

671
00:31:17,611 --> 00:31:19,012
Vincent filled me in,

672
00:31:19,045 --> 00:31:21,045
showed me what really
happened in that alley.

673
00:31:30,279 --> 00:31:31,912
But why, Morgan?

674
00:31:31,945 --> 00:31:33,945
Why would you do that?

675
00:31:37,845 --> 00:31:39,745
I loved
Cadence Bixby.

676
00:31:39,778 --> 00:31:43,512
From the moment I laid eyes
on her, through this window,

677
00:31:43,546 --> 00:31:45,945
I loved Cadence Bixby.

678
00:31:45,978 --> 00:31:48,512
I watched her up
here for months--

679
00:31:48,546 --> 00:31:50,546
getting ready for
work in the morning,

680
00:31:50,578 --> 00:31:52,512
coming home from
work in the evening--

681
00:31:52,546 --> 00:31:53,878
and I thought
to myself,

682
00:31:53,912 --> 00:31:57,345
"My God, if I could just
get close to this woman,

683
00:31:57,379 --> 00:32:01,112
if I could just matter
to this woman."

684
00:32:01,145 --> 00:32:02,245
And then,

685
00:32:02,279 --> 00:32:04,546
I decided to
follow her.

686
00:32:04,578 --> 00:32:07,212
I wanted to know more than
what I saw from up here--

687
00:32:07,245 --> 00:32:10,379
where she worked,
where she ate.

688
00:32:10,412 --> 00:32:12,112
And then I discovered
the shelter.

689
00:32:12,145 --> 00:32:15,546
It took me weeks to get up
the courage to go in.

690
00:32:15,578 --> 00:32:17,145
And once I did,

691
00:32:17,179 --> 00:32:20,012
once I was actually
close to her,

692
00:32:20,045 --> 00:32:23,446
she was even more beautiful,
more special.

693
00:32:23,479 --> 00:32:27,512
And I never knew what to do,
and I never knew what to say.

694
00:32:27,546 --> 00:32:30,546
I just kept
adopting cats.

695
00:32:30,578 --> 00:32:33,079
It was the one
thing that worked.

696
00:32:33,112 --> 00:32:36,112
Whenever I did it, she'd
be mine for a half hour.

697
00:32:36,145 --> 00:32:40,412
Asong as it took to fill out
the paperwork, she'd be mi.

698
00:32:40,446 --> 00:32:41,912
But that still
doesn't explain...

699
00:32:41,945 --> 00:32:44,412
Doesn't it?

700
00:32:44,446 --> 00:32:46,611
I showed her to him--

701
00:32:46,645 --> 00:32:50,045
right here, a little
more than a year ago.

702
00:32:50,079 --> 00:32:54,212
I thought if he saw her, he
could understand why she was

703
00:32:54,245 --> 00:32:56,578
the only thing I
ever talked about.

704
00:32:56,611 --> 00:32:58,778
I guess he understood
more than I knew.

705
00:32:58,812 --> 00:33:02,045
I can't believe
he kept that from you,

706
00:33:02,079 --> 00:33:03,778
knowing what you were
planning to do.

707
00:33:03,812 --> 00:33:06,279
<i>But it was his
plan, Mrs. Dubois.</i>

708
00:33:06,312 --> 00:33:07,812
It was his idea.

709
00:33:07,845 --> 00:33:10,611
The million-dollar insurance
policy, the staged mugging--

710
00:33:10,645 --> 00:33:11,711
it was all his idea.

711
00:33:11,745 --> 00:33:12,945
He just talked
me into it.

712
00:33:12,978 --> 00:33:16,145
This doesn't make sense.

713
00:33:16,179 --> 00:33:19,878
How can anyone possibly talk you
into letting them kill you?

714
00:33:21,945 --> 00:33:25,179
I'd been threatening to do it
to myself for years.

715
00:33:25,212 --> 00:33:28,279
Suddenly, it all made sense.

716
00:33:28,312 --> 00:33:30,711
I could put myself
out of the pain I was in

717
00:33:30,745 --> 00:33:33,945
and give her
this remarkable gift.

718
00:33:33,978 --> 00:33:35,412
I would matter to her.

719
00:33:38,645 --> 00:33:40,412
And little did you know,

720
00:33:40,446 --> 00:33:42,645
all that money wouldn't
just be going to Cadence.

721
00:33:42,678 --> 00:33:45,611
It would eventually find
its way to her new husband,

722
00:33:45,645 --> 00:33:48,479
your best friend, Nick.

723
00:33:48,512 --> 00:33:52,446
I'm really depressed.

724
00:33:52,479 --> 00:33:55,912
I haven't felt
this suicidal since...

725
00:33:55,945 --> 00:33:58,079
since I was alive.

726
00:33:58,112 --> 00:34:02,479
Well, maybe there's something
we can do about that.

727
00:34:08,264 --> 00:34:09,564
Where is she?

728
00:34:09,598 --> 00:34:12,030
Ms. Bixby is waiting for you
in the conference room.

729
00:34:12,064 --> 00:34:13,598
I believe you know the way.

730
00:34:27,264 --> 00:34:30,031
Cade...

731
00:34:30,064 --> 00:34:31,264
I don't know
what these people

732
00:34:31,298 --> 00:34:32,497
have been filling
your head with,

733
00:34:32,530 --> 00:34:36,630
but I'm here to tell you
it's not true.

734
00:34:36,664 --> 00:34:38,730
I called a lawyer;
he's on his way.

735
00:34:38,764 --> 00:34:41,197
But I don't
understand.

736
00:34:41,231 --> 00:34:44,064
Why would you
do that, Nick?

737
00:34:44,097 --> 00:34:46,630
If everything they
told me wasn't true,

738
00:34:46,664 --> 00:34:48,197
why would you even
need a lawyer?

739
00:34:48,231 --> 00:34:50,530
Come on.

740
00:34:50,563 --> 00:34:51,697
Let's talk about this outside.

741
00:34:51,730 --> 00:34:53,197
What's wrong
with right here?

742
00:34:53,231 --> 00:34:56,797
We don't have
anything to hide.

743
00:34:56,830 --> 00:34:58,231
Do we?

744
00:34:58,264 --> 00:35:00,298
Cadence was just telling us
how odd she found it

745
00:35:00,331 --> 00:35:02,164
that it wasn't until
Morgan passed away

746
00:35:02,197 --> 00:35:04,463
that you even mentioned
that he was your friend.

747
00:35:05,387 --> 00:35:07,596
Darling...

748
00:35:07,597 --> 00:35:09,263
I explained that already.

749
00:35:09,296 --> 00:35:11,730
He and I weren't
getting along.

750
00:35:11,763 --> 00:35:13,697
We weren't speaking,
that's all.

751
00:35:13,730 --> 00:35:14,697
I loved him,

752
00:35:14,730 --> 00:35:17,563
but he was a depressed,
moody guy.

753
00:35:17,597 --> 00:35:19,830
If I'd known you two had
already met through the shelter,

754
00:35:19,863 --> 00:35:21,296
don't you think
I would've told you?

755
00:35:21,330 --> 00:35:23,697
I wish you had.

756
00:35:23,730 --> 00:35:25,463
Because considering
the amount of money

757
00:35:25,496 --> 00:35:28,730
he was planning on leaving
me, it would've been nice

758
00:35:28,763 --> 00:35:31,763
to get to know him
a little better.

759
00:35:31,797 --> 00:35:33,830
Maybe even have him
over for dinner.

760
00:35:33,863 --> 00:35:36,296
Now, that would have been
a fascinating dinner.

761
00:35:36,330 --> 00:35:38,096
You, your best friend,

762
00:35:38,129 --> 00:35:39,997
and the woman you were seeing
behind his back.

763
00:35:41,330 --> 00:35:42,496
Might have made it
more difficult

764
00:35:42,530 --> 00:35:43,863
convincing him to let you
shoot him, though.

765
00:35:43,897 --> 00:35:47,597
Look, Morgan was killed
by a stranger,

766
00:35:47,630 --> 00:35:49,163
a mugger.

767
00:35:49,196 --> 00:35:51,463
I know you're under
a lot of pressure.

768
00:35:51,496 --> 00:35:54,129
I'm sorry you're having trouble
finding the person who did this.

769
00:35:54,163 --> 00:35:56,129
But if you think
I'm gonna stand here

770
00:35:56,163 --> 00:35:58,797
and let you
accuse me of...

771
00:35:58,830 --> 00:35:59,930
of hurting my friend...

772
00:35:59,964 --> 00:36:02,663
Funny thing about muggings,
Mr. Lewin--

773
00:36:02,697 --> 00:36:03,930
the money that gets stolen

774
00:36:03,964 --> 00:36:05,563
often doesn't stay
with the mugger very long.

775
00:36:05,597 --> 00:36:07,064
It gets spent.

776
00:36:07,096 --> 00:36:09,997
Which is unfortunate, because
it frequently contains evidence

777
00:36:10,030 --> 00:36:12,863
that connects the mugger
to the crime.

778
